We solve this problem for any sequence having $n$ terms by applying induction with respect to $n$.

The case $n=1$ is clear. Suppose that the statement if true for all sequences of length less than $n$. Now consider a sequence $a_1, a_2, \dots, a_n$.

\textit{Case 1: $a_1$ is not a leading term.}

Then the set of all leading terms of the sequence $a_1, a_2, \dots, a_n$ coincides with the set of all leading terms of the sequence $a_2, a_3, \dots, a_{2003}$ and by inductive hypothesis we are done.

\textit{Case 2: $a_1$ is a leading term.}

Consider the smallest nonnegative integer $m$ with positive $a_1 + a_2 + \dots + a_m$. Then the terms $a_2, a_3, \dots, a_m$ are also leading terms and their sum is positive. The sum of all remaining leading terms also is nonnegative by induction hypothesis.
